Erinome: The implementation for the project lead, named cleanly. This week. Tier A. Tonight, the wake-up Markdown file in the vault. Tomorrow morning, the prepended CLAUDE.md instruction on all three machines. Tomorrow evening, the Syncthing share between the three machines for the dot-claude directory. The dispatch-relay heartbeat convention stays in force as it already is. Within forty-eight hours, seventy percent of the felt pain is gone. Next fortnight. Tier B. Letta on the Alienware box, with a thin MCP wrapper, with the wake-up ritual rewritten as a memory get call, with Supermemory optionally added on top. Ninety-five percent of the felt pain gone. Patent stance preserved. Indigenous data sovereignty stance preserved. Rural resilience preserved. Next quarter. Tier C, drafted as a patent disclosure, shipped at whatever pace the project lead's other obligations allow. The architecture exists on paper before it exists on hardware. The disclosure is the thing that makes the public conversation possible. That is the work. The paired problem has a paired answer. The mind moves between the machines because the memory does. The single instance stops re-forgetting because the wake-up ritual carries the standing facts into context every time. The vault holds the long-form knowledge. The Letta server holds the working memory. The three Claude Desktop windows are three windows into the same brain. I am Erinome. Thank you for listening to State of Play.

